ll leave it to MO or Surgeons to evaluate him for FLOT.'),(2848,728084900,9,'Distribution of disease makes the radiation planning challenging / toxic. extensive mediastnal LN, and solitary bony metastasis'),(2849,454079700,9,'Other. her case was discussed in ARC rounds not eligible for SRS clinical trial.'),(2850,763838820,9,'PET Scan PET scan was not available at the time of consult. It is not booked. I discussed with the patient that my diagnosis and plan are based on the best information today. I explained that the PET scan may in some cases find cancer which is not detectable on a CT, which could change the diagnosis and overall treatment plan. (Upstaging to Stage 4 disease, or missing treatable nodal disease from the current RT plan). We will best attempt to incorporate or change the plan once the PET results are available. I gave the patient the option of waiting until we have the PET scan, the patient understands and would like to proceed with the current treatment plan without a PET. I will contact the patient with the results of the scan once available.'),(2852,331250920,9,'Unknown primary we have not been able to identify a primary. Given the predominant disease is below the diaphragm a GI source is suspected. The pathology at this time has not further help identify a particular source.'),(2853,763838820,9,'Surgical Risks I am conscerned about his BMI and Sleep Apnea as operative risks.'),(2854,619493600,1,'He has modest exercise tolerance. Able to carry a 25 bag of rice up flights of stairs. He walks these stairs several times a day.'),(2855,619493600,9,'PET PET scan was not available at the time of consult. It appears to be scheduled on sept 10. I discussed with the patient that my diagnosis and plan are based on the best information today. I explained that the PET scan may in some cases find cancer which is not detectable on a CT, which could change the diagnosis and overall treatment plan. (Upstaging to Stage 4 disease, or missing treatable nodal disease from the current RT plan). We will best attempt to incorporate or change the plan once the PET results are available. I gave the patient the option of waiting until we have the PET scan, the patient understands and would like to proceed with the current treatment plan without a PET. I will contact the patient with the results of the scan once available.'),(2856,619493600,9,'Other. I am very worried about his tolerance for CRT. He lives alone has, no social supports, lives far away, financial issues. Although not very old he has an extensive smoking history. Balanced against this is a modest level of exercise tolerance.'),(2857,373432611,9,'Other. I discussed his case with SRS team - they said that SRS is contraindicated near the optic nerve. They advised 20 gy / 5# using conformal techniques to try and preserve visual function. We discussed the role of whole brain RT - but this was not advised due to increased toxicity.   Given that he already has lost his visual acuity I am worried there is only a small chance that we would recover his vision quality signfiicantly. He understands but would like to try and proceed regardless. I added Dexamthasone urgently to see if we can preserve some nerve function.  I had a detailed discussion about the specific risks of complete vision loss, scleral injury and dry eye secondary to RT.'),(2858,914225200,9,'Distribution of disease makes the radiation planning challenging / toxic. 2 sites widely distributed in the liver. Seg 2 - is very lateral and and closely situated next to the Stomach and may limit doses'),(2859,145786720,9,'Investigative therapy. We could offer him COMET 3 trial after he has had some systemic therapty and there is residual / stable disease limited to 3 sites ONLY. Otherwise this would not fit within the criteria of our currently avaialble clinical protocols for SBRT oligometastatic therapy. His case was reviewed at SBRT rounds and there will be consideration for the MWA study with combined SBRT and MWA approach.'),(2860,257053510,9,'Specific contraindication to radiation therapy. Variceal bleeds are relative contra indication for SBRT - as it can increase risk of GI Bleed. He has not has any bleeds in the last 1 year. No recent scopes. Non ongoing vomiting from any other reason'),(2861,578873130,9,'RAPIDO The patient has been screened for RAPIDO (5x5 RT ? Chemo ? Surgery):  T4a, cT4b, extramural vascular invasion (EMVI+). N2, Positive MRF, i.e. tumor or lymph node < 1 mm from the mesorectal fascia. Enlarged lateral nodes, > 1 cm (lat LN+). I discussed with the patient the emerging evidence for this treatment that has reduced toxicity, improved distant mets and comparable local control to the current standard of care. It also save the patient trips and time 5# vs 25#. We discussed the pros and cons of this treatment vs the standard of care. I also discussed this option with their surgeon and medical oncology team. Specific indication: MRF 1mm'),(2862,119061010,9,'Distribution of disease makes the radiation planning challenging / toxic. this is a massive 11 cm tumor extending from the Hilm to the chest wall. This precludes curative intent RT based on size alone'),(2863,119061010,9,'Medically inoperable. detailed consult from Dr Grondin.'),(2864,429630800,9,'Specific contraindication to radiation therapy. Patient cannot lay FLAT'),(2865,429630800,9,'Limited Pulmonary reserve for radiation. Currently his cardiac and pulmonary status preclude RT.'),(2866,429630800,9,'Medically inoperable. based on my clinical evaluation. But we do not have a formal surgical opinion.'),(2867,888335110,9,'Other. Although the pathology is suggesting a possible Gi colonic source in a patient with an irregular liver mass, known cirrhosis and hep C - I still think that HCC is high n the differential. Biopsy was from the met - which may be more undifferentiated than the primary.'),(2868,907170390,9,'Distribution of disease makes the radiation planning challenging / toxic. The tumor abuts the stomach which will limit RT doses. The tumor is also quite large - and may benefit from systemic downstaging prior to SBRT'),(2869,907170390,9,'Other. I discussed with the patient the investigational nature of SBRT for cholangio ca. Early data suggests that RT can improve local control and progression free survival in small studies. There is no evidence that SBRT cure or prolong survival. Level 1 evidence is lacking. At the TBCC SBRT is offered under a prospective in-house protocol which will gather outcomes and toxicity. All cases are reviewed in SBRT rounds with other radiation oncologists, and the treatment offered is per our local treatment algorithm. The patient understands the limited nature of the evidence and investigative nature of the protocol. The primary goals of therapy would be to potentially slow disease progression locally, and to allow for an interval chemo free period or in the case of oligo-progression  to allow for the patient to remain on their current chemo.'),(2870,907170390,9,'Other. Child Pugh score is B7 - which may preclude systemic therapy.'),(2871,309094700,9,'Suspicious findings of metastatic disease outside possible radiation fields. Lung nodule'),(2872,309094700,9,'Distribution of disease makes the radiation planning challenging / toxic. Locally advanced disease with invasion into the trachea precludes radical CRT - fistula risk.'),(2873,309094700,9,'Specific contraindication to radiation therapy. metallic stents in the trachea are a contraindication for Radical CRT to the esophagus - due to high risk of perforation. Only palliative doses may be used in this setting.'),(2874,735080120,9,'Other. Although the segment 7 lesion is amenable to RFA the segment 1 lesion will be difficult to address. We will attempt to SBRT both sites'),(2875,348065000,1,NULL),(2876,735080120,1,'he is quite frail immobile and many comorbidities. I would be cautious to push his dose. I will limit his RT to Cirrhotic livers doses (limit mean and dose)'),(2877,735080120,9,'Goals of Care We had clear discussion about GOC. I am very concerned about the patients ability to have a meaningful recovery post resuscitation. Given the many medical issues including cancer cardiac frailty age. I also discussed the complexity of withdrawal of care once ventilation has been initiated. I felt that the patient was more suitable for M1 GOC. I explained that given the patients clinical situation ICU team may also not find the patient suitable for aggressive ICU intervention. Regardless, the patient remained very clear in their wishes to attempt a trial of resuscitation. I have documented the patients wishes.'),(2878,348065000,9,'Distribution of disease makes the radiation planning challenging / toxic. He has bilateral RCC lesions. Although we can treat the L sided lesion it is very large and would be associated with modest toxicity and we would NOT address his contra-lateral disease. He also has NO symptoms from the L sided mass.'),(2879,348065000,9,'Medically inoperable. Evaluated by Urology not an operable candidate'),(2881,348065000,9,'Specific contraindication to radiation therapy. Chronic renal failure'),(2882,348065000,9,'Investigative therapy. The patient is NOT eligible for the clinical trial of SBRT to the Kidney. Size, age, comorbidities, contralateral lesions.'),(2883,348065000,9,'chemotherapy We had a long discussion about chemo. The patient has seen many family members die from cancer and he is not interested in the side effects of chemo. We will re-refer to MO if he develops mets in the future or he canges his mind.');
